INSERT INTO fs_study_modules
  (id, module_number, title, description, week_range, exam_weight_percent, key_topics, key_formulas, content_sections, prerequisite_module, passing_score, question_count, icon, xp_reward, is_published, review_status)
VALUES (
 'f500000b-0000-0000-0000-00000000000b', 11,
 'Business, Ethics & Professional Practice',
 'The NCEES FS "Business Concepts" knowledge area (11-17 scored questions): business entity types, contracts, engineering economics, professional ethics and the NCEES Model Rules, professional liability and standard of care, and field safety (OSHA). High-yield, mostly conceptual points that many candidates neglect.',
 'Weeks 15-16', 13,
 ARRAY['Business entity types (sole proprietorship, partnership, LLC, PLLC, corporation, PC)','Contract elements: offer, acceptance, consideration, capacity, legality','Types of contracts and breach/remedies','Engineering economics: simple & compound interest','Present worth, future worth, and annuities','Straight-line depreciation','Professional ethics — public health, safety & welfare paramount','NCEES Model Rules of Professional Conduct','Professional liability, standard of care, and negligence','Confidential information and conflicts of interest','OSHA field safety: confined spaces, PPE, work-zone traffic control','Project management: scope, schedule, budget, proposals & invoicing']::text[],
 '[{"name":"Simple Interest","formula":"I = P · i · n   (interest only; balance owed = P + I)"},{"name":"Compound Future Worth","formula":"F = P(1 + i)^n"},{"name":"Present Worth (single sum)","formula":"P = F / (1 + i)^n"},{"name":"Uniform Series Future Worth (annuity)","formula":"F = A · [((1 + i)^n − 1) / i]"},{"name":"Capital Recovery (loan payment)","formula":"A = P · [ i(1 + i)^n / ((1 + i)^n − 1) ]"},{"name":"Straight-Line Depreciation","formula":"D = (C − S) / n   (C = cost, S = salvage, n = life)"}]'::jsonb,
 '[{"type":"overview","title":"Module Overview","content":"## Why this module matters\n\n**Business Concepts is worth 11-17 scored questions** on the NCEES FS exam — roughly the same weight as GNSS/Geodesy or Photogrammetry, yet it is the area technically-minded candidates most often skip. The questions are almost all **conceptual and fast**: entity types, the elements of a contract, an interest calculation, an ethics rule. There is very little math, and what math exists (engineering economics) follows a handful of formulas. Point-for-point, this is some of the **cheapest score on the exam** — do not leave it blank.\n\nThis module covers five threads:\n\n- **Business organization** — how a surveying firm is structured (sole proprietorship, partnership, LLC/PLLC, corporation/PC) and what that means for liability and taxes.\n- **Contracts** — the elements that make an agreement enforceable, common contract types, and what happens on breach.\n- **Engineering economics** — the time value of money: simple vs compound interest, present/future worth, annuities, and depreciation.\n- **Professional ethics & conduct** — the NCEES Model Rules, with the surveyor''s paramount duty to protect the public''s health, safety, and welfare.\n- **Professional practice & safety** — standard of care, liability, and OSHA field safety (confined spaces, PPE, work-zone traffic control).\n\nTreat these as reflex knowledge. On exam day, a Business question should take under a minute and bank a guaranteed point while you save clock for the long COGO problems."},{"type":"concepts","title":"Key Concepts","content":"## Business entity types\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"6\">\n<tr><th>Entity</th><th>Owners</th><th>Liability</th><th>Notes</th></tr>\n<tr><td><b>Sole proprietorship</b></td><td>One</td><td><b>Unlimited</b> personal</td><td>Simplest & most common small business; owner and business are one</td></tr>\n<tr><td><b>Partnership</b></td><td>Two or more, for profit</td><td>Unlimited (general); joint &amp; several</td><td>A business owned by two or more people working for a profit</td></tr>\n<tr><td><b>LLC / PLLC</b></td><td>One or more members</td><td><b>Limited</b> to investment</td><td>PLLC = the professional form required for licensed practice in many states</td></tr>\n<tr><td><b>Corporation / PC</b></td><td>Shareholders</td><td>Limited</td><td>Exists <b>independently</b> of its owners; can <b>sell stock/shares</b>; PC = professional corporation</td></tr>\n</table>\n\nExam tells: a **partnership** is *a business owned by two or more people working for a profit*; a **corporation** *exists independently of the people who own and manage it* and *can sell stock*; a **sole proprietorship** is the *most common* form. Professional surveying practice usually must be through a **PLLC or PC** (a licensee must be responsible).\n\n## Contracts\n\nAn enforceable contract requires five elements:\n\n1. **Offer** — a definite proposal.\n2. **Acceptance** — agreement to the offer''s terms (mutual assent / \"meeting of the minds\").\n3. **Consideration** — something of **value** exchanged by both parties (money, services, or a promise). Consideration need not be money, but both parties must bargain for it.\n4. **Capacity** — the parties are legally able to contract (of age, sound mind, authority to sign for an entity).\n5. **Legality** — a lawful purpose and subject matter.\n\n**Breach** is failure to perform; remedies include damages, specific performance, or rescission. Know that **consideration = the value given**, distinct from the *names of the parties*, *legal subject matter*, or *authority to sign* (which are other requirements).\n\n## Professional ethics — the Model Rules\n\nThe **NCEES Model Rules of Professional Conduct** are the template most state boards adopt. The single most-tested principle:\n\n> Licensees'' **first and foremost responsibility is to protect the health, safety, and welfare of the public** when performing services for clients and employers.\n\nOther core duties: practice **only in your area of competence**; be **objective and truthful**; **avoid conflicts of interest** (disclose any that are unavoidable); protect **confidential** client information; do not offer/accept improper inducements; and sign/seal only work you prepared or directly supervised.\n\n## Professional liability & standard of care\n\nA surveyor is held to the **standard of care** — the degree of skill and diligence a reasonably prudent surveyor would exercise under similar conditions. Falling below it, causing damages, is **negligence**. Liability is managed with professional-liability (errors &amp; omissions) insurance, good documentation, and clear scope. A **warranty deed** (from boundary law) is a *title guarantee*; a professional''s work product carries the standard of care, not a guarantee of perfection.\n\n## Field safety (OSHA)\n\nSurveyors work in traffic, near excavation, and in confined spaces. Key OSHA ideas:\n\n- A **confined space** is (1) large enough to enter and perform work, (2) has **limited or restricted means of entry/exit**, and (3) is **not designed for continuous occupancy** (e.g., manholes, vaults, tanks). A **permit-required** confined space additionally contains or could contain a hazardous atmosphere, engulfment risk, or other recognized serious hazard.\n- **PPE**: high-visibility apparel in work zones, hard hats, eye protection.\n- **Work-zone traffic control** follows the MUTCD; call **811 / One-Call** before any subsurface work."},{"type":"formulas","title":"Essential Formulas (Engineering Economics)","content":"## Time value of money\n\n**Simple interest** (interest on the original principal only):\n\nI = P · i · n     balance owed = P + I = P(1 + i·n)\n\nwhere P = principal, i = interest rate per period, n = number of periods.\n\n**Compound interest — future worth of a single sum:**\n\nF = P(1 + i)^n\n\n**Present worth of a single future sum:**\n\nP = F / (1 + i)^n\n\n## Uniform series (annuities)\n\n**Future worth of a uniform series** of end-of-period payments A:\n\nF = A · [ ((1 + i)^n − 1) / i ]\n\n**Capital recovery** — the level payment A that repays a present loan P:\n\nA = P · [ i(1 + i)^n / ((1 + i)^n − 1) ]\n\n## Depreciation (straight-line)\n\nD = (C − S) / n\n\nwhere C = initial cost, S = salvage value, n = useful life (years). Book value after k years = C − k·D.\n\n## A note on declining-balance loan interest\n\nWhen a loan is repaid with **equal principal payments plus interest on the remaining balance**, the interest each year is i × (outstanding balance). Total interest is the **sum over all years** — see Worked Example 1. This is the exact pattern of the practice-exam financing question."},{"type":"examples","title":"Worked Examples","content":"## Example 1 — Cost of financing (simple interest on a declining balance)\n\nA firm finances a $40,000 total station at 8% simple interest, repaying $8,000 of principal plus interest at the end of each year for 5 years. What is the total added cost of financing vs paying cash?\n\nInterest each year = 8% × outstanding balance:\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"6\">\n<tr><th>Year</th><th>Balance</th><th>Interest (8%)</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>$40,000</td><td>$3,200</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>$32,000</td><td>$2,560</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3</td><td>$24,000</td><td>$1,920</td></tr>\n<tr><td>4</td><td>$16,000</td><td>$1,280</td></tr>\n<tr><td>5</td><td>$8,000</td><td>$640</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n**Total interest = 3,200 + 2,560 + 1,920 + 1,280 + 640 = $9,600.** That is the added cost of financing.\n\n## Example 2 — Compound future worth\n\n$10,000 is invested at 6% compounded annually for 8 years. Future value?\n\nF = P(1 + i)^n = 10,000(1.06)^8 = 10,000(1.5938) = **$15,938.**\n\n## Example 3 — Present worth\n\nHow much must be deposited today at 5% to have $25,000 in 10 years?\n\nP = F/(1 + i)^n = 25,000/(1.05)^10 = 25,000/1.6289 = **$15,347.**\n\n## Example 4 — Straight-line depreciation\n\nA $60,000 survey vehicle has a $12,000 salvage value and a 6-year life. Annual depreciation and book value after 4 years?\n\nD = (C − S)/n = (60,000 − 12,000)/6 = **$8,000/yr.** Book value after 4 yr = 60,000 − 4(8,000) = **$28,000.**\n\n## Example 5 — Contract consideration\n\nA client promises to pay a surveyor $5,000 to stake a subdivision, and the surveyor promises to perform the work. What supplies the *consideration*? The **value exchanged** — the payment on one side and the promised services on the other. (The parties'' names, the legal subject matter, and authority to sign are separate contract requirements, not the consideration.)\n\n## Example 6 — Ethics / confined space\n\nA crew must take shots inside a storm-drain vault. Which statements are true? It is a **confined space** because it is large enough to enter, has restricted entry/exit, and is not designed for continuous occupancy; and it may be **permit-required** if it can contain a hazardous atmosphere. The surveyor''s **first duty is the crew''s and public''s safety** — test the atmosphere and follow the permit program before entry."},{"type":"tips","title":"Exam Tips & Strategy","content":"## Strategy for Business questions\n\n- **Bank them fast.** Most are one-line conceptual recalls (entity type, a contract element, an ethics rule). Answer immediately and move on; save the clock for COGO/curves.\n- **Ethics: the public comes first — always.** When an ethics question offers \"protect the client,\" \"protect your employer,\" \"protect the public,\" or \"protect the profession,\" the answer is almost always **the public''s health, safety, and welfare.**\n- **Consideration = value exchanged.** Do not confuse it with the other contract requirements (offer, acceptance, capacity, legality) or with identifying the parties.\n- **Entity tells:** *two or more people for profit* = partnership; *exists independently / sells stock* = corporation; *most common* = sole proprietorship; *licensed professional practice* usually = PLLC/PC.\n- **Simple vs compound interest.** \"Simple\" = interest on the original principal only (or on the declining balance for a loan repaid in equal principal chunks). \"Compound\" = interest on interest, F = P(1+i)^n. Read which one the problem states.\n- **Confined space = 3 tests** (enter &amp; work + limited entry/exit + not for continuous occupancy). \"Designed for continuous occupancy\" is the classic wrong choice — it is the *opposite* of the definition.\n- **Standard of care, not a guarantee.** A surveyor is liable for negligence (falling below the standard of care), not for failing to be perfect.\n\n## Common traps\n\n- Picking \"protect the client/employer\" over the **public** on an ethics question.\n- Confusing **consideration** with the *names of the parties* or *legal subject matter*.\n- Treating a loan''s **simple interest on a declining balance** as if it were a flat rate on the full principal every year.\n- Calling a space \"confined\" only if it is dangerous — the base definition is about size, entry/exit, and occupancy; the *hazard* is what makes it **permit-required**.\n- Assuming a corporation and a partnership have the same liability — a corporation/LLC **limits** owner liability; a general partnership/sole proprietorship does **not**.\n\n## How the handbook helps\n\nThe FS Reference Handbook''s engineering-economics section provides the interest and worth factors (single-payment, uniform-series, capital-recovery) and the straight-line depreciation relation. Ethics and business-organization questions are recall — no lookup — so commit the entity table and the \"public welfare paramount\" rule to memory before exam day."}]'::jsonb,
 8, 70, 24, '💼', 400, true, 'approved')
